h3. Problem Definition  

* Currently, there's no way to change the color of the text of the 'Macro Suggestion'. Its default color is black and when highlighted, it turns blue.

h3. Suggested Solution  

* Provide an option on the "Color Scheme" page so any administrator can change the layout of the text provided by the Macro Browser

h3. Why this is important   

* Some users may use a dark color for the "Menu Item Selected Background". You cannot read the text due to that. Here's an example:
 !example.png|thumbnail! 

h3. Workaround 
You can apply the following to your global CSS stylesheet to edit the selected text colour - adjust color: as needed:
{code:java}
.aui-dropdown li.active span {
	background-color: transparent;
	color: #FFFFFF;
}{code}

h3. Issue Summary

When using the Jira Issue Filter macro in Confluence, you can't enter a JQL as shown below.
{code}assignee was admin during ("2019/01/01", "2019/02/05"){code}

This JQL works fine in Jira and will display the results as expected, but Confluence throws an error message instead.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Link Confluence to Jira via application links.
# In Jira, run this JQL to confirm that it works and results are returned (change accordingly based on your instance).
 {code}assignee was admin during ("2019/01/01", "2019/02/05"){code}
# Create a new page and insert the Jira Issue Filter macro.
# Add in the following JQL to the macro.
 {code}assignee was admin during ("2019/01/01", "2019/02/05"){code}

h3. Expected Results
The same results should be displayed in Confluence as it did in Jira.

h3. Actual Results
Confluence displays the following error message.
{quote}The Jira server didn't understand your search query. If you entered JQL, please ensure that it's correctly formed. If you entered an issue key, ensure that it exists and you have permission to view it.{quote}

h3. Workaround
Add in another condition to the JQL. Any of these examples will work, so long as the condition you define is valid (i.e. a project by key 'test' and a user called 'foo' exists).
{code}project=test and assignee was admin during ("2019/01/01", "2019/02/05"){code}
{code}assignee=foo or assignee was admin during ("2019/01/01", "2019/02/05"){code}

In our web based inhouse application we are displaying certain Confluence pages via iframe - an apache httpd takes care of x-frame-options. The pages are displayed as idented.

Issue:
If a user invokes an ajax-request in our web app after scrolling within the confluence page/iframe and not returning to its top, the Chrome tab freezes and must be restarted. This is caused by an endless loop in a javascript provided by Confluence.

 !adjustHeader-bug-public.gif! 

Bug:
The file `atlassian\confluence\confluence\WEB-INF\atlassian-bundled-plugins\confluence-fixed-headers-1.4.0.jar\js\utils\dom.js` contains a function called `adjustMainHeaderSize` which takes care of positioning the breadcrumb and sidebar within Confluence. This function is called by a `MutationObserver` which itself is initialized in `js\confluence-fixed-headers.js`. The observer listens on changes for the style-attribute. If a change occurs the observer is called and therefore `adjustMainHeaderSize`, which itself changes the style-attribute resulting in a new observer call and so forth.

h3. Workaround

The function `adjustMainHeaderSize` uses jQuery's `outerWidth` to calculate new values. But `outerWidth` relies on changing style attributes. This issue is already solved by Atlassian for the function `updateTableStickyHeaderOption`, which is located just below `adjustMainHeaderSize`


Therefore we applied a similiar approach for our Confluence instance and succeeded.

{code}
function o() { /* 3270: adjustMainHeaderSize */
k();
/* BUG: jQuery.outerWidth() uses jQuery.swap() and causes endless loop
var x = d.outerWidth() - (parseInt(d.css("padding-left")) + parseInt(d.css("padding-right")));
*/
var style = window.getComputedStyle ? getComputedStyle(d[0]) : d[0].style;
var x = d[0].offsetWidth - parseInt(style.paddingLeft) - parseInt(style.paddingRight);
if (x > 0 && x != this.lastValue) {
this.lastValue = x;
n.css({
width: x
})
}
}
```

